  <title role="Vision and scope document">
    Documenting the Project's Vision and Scope 
  </title>

  <section><title>Introduction</title>
    <para> 
      The Vision and Scope document is an extremely important document featuring the
      high-level business objectives and how the system is expected to address them. Often even
      senior management would be involved in the development and review of this document. To
      this end it should be kept fairly concise with non-core information banished to referenced 
      documents.
    </para>
    <para> 
      Like most requirements documents, this document is expected to evolve over time.
      In order to make this evolution tractable and to not re-expose stake holders to information
      they have previously absorbed, it is often a good idea to stick with a core Vision and
      Scope document with new issues documented in so-called “Delta Vision and Scope Documents”
      which contain only the changes and additions from previous versions.
    </para>
    <section>
      <title>The Vision &amp; Scope Document provides the framework for all future requirements</title>
      <para>
        In the context of use-case driven, iterative software development processes, the 
        <emphasis>Requirements Specification</emphasis> is an iterative
        document for which the detailed requirements for the use cases are added
        as the use cases are to be realized. The Vision &amp; Scope document, on the other
        hand, is the document which is developed up front and which specifies the framework
        and scoping for the remainder of the project.
        
        <note>
          <para>
            The Vision &amp; Scope not only needs to be available early because it provides the framework 
            for all future requirements specifications. It also provides the core input for the architectural
            process. The architecture is more driven by the non-functional requirements (the required
            quality attributes) than the detailed functional requirements.
          </para>
          <para>
            The Vision &amp; Scope  document is in some ways for the requirements process what
            the architecture is for the development process. Both, the vision and scope and the
            architecture are specified up front, while the detailed use case requirements and the
            system design are both done iteratively in the context of iterative software development
            processes.
        </para>
        </note>
      </para>
    </section>
  </section>

